{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b53a0c59-6367-4cdb-99bf-9a6f73c783e3","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9, so you have access to all the modern patterns. Here's the recommended approach:\n\n- **Constructor** — for synchronous init + `TestContext` injection (supported since MSTest 3.3)\n- **`[TestInitialize] async Task`** — for asynchronous init\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly HttpClient _client;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Asynchronous initialization here\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n        TestContext.WriteLine(\"Ready\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup()\n    {\n        _client.Dispose();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `TestContext` is injected via the constructor — no need for the legacy static property + `[ClassInitialize]` pattern\n- The constructor handles sync setup; `[TestInitialize]` handles async setup\n- Only one `[TestInitialize]` per class is allowed, but it can be `async Task`\n- For cleanup, you can also implement `IAsyncDisposable` instead of `[TestCleanup]`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e660ebd2-5b10-477e-b66b-d656bd81cebc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach for initialization and TestContext injection uses:\n\n1. **`TestContext`** — In MSTest v3, `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (since MSTest 3.3+). The old pattern was a static property with `[ClassInitialize]`, but now you can just accept it as a constructor parameter.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization** — `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization** — In MSTest v3, `[TestInitialize]` methods can be `async Task`.\n\n\n4. **Cleanup patterns** — You can implement `IAsyncDisposable` or `IDisposable` for resource cleanup.\n\nThe modern pattern in MSTest 3.3+ involves injecting TestContext through the constructor rather than using a public property.\n\nActually, I need to clarify something about `[TestInitialize]` — you can only have one per class, so if you need both sync and async setup, the best approach is to make the single `[TestInitialize]` method async and handle all initialization there, whether it's sync or async work.\n\nThe cleanest pattern is to use the constructor for synchronous field setup, then use a single async `[TestInitialize]` method for any async operations, and inject `TestContext` through the constructor.","outputTokens":938,"requestId":"1BD5:4309A:4D1AF7:582DC2:6A03D72C"},"id":"c88d1778-9920-4f89-b763-8c717bcbed0d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:43:27.303Z","parentId":"543b265c-3e18-4ab3-b2cb-904142f55a48"}
